Detailed Description

The class CallHdl is intended to represent a single mobile originated or mobile terminated voice call. Multi-party calls are not represented by this class. The class provides methods for all common opertations on single voice calls, like Setup, Release, Accept, Hold, Retrieve, etc. Furthermore, methods are available to access call-related data, like the corresponding phone number, the type of call, information transferred by the network (e.g. supplementary service code), the time of setup, the state of a call (active, held, setup) etc..
Additional methods which indicate if the corresponding operation is permitted for the respective CallHdl are alse available. The corresponding operations are Setup, Accept, Hold, Retrieve, Explicit Call Transfer, and Start/StopDtmfToneGeneration.
The class keeps a reference to a call (CallIndex). This CallIndex refers to a call which may be active, held or in setup phase. If a CallHdl object does not refer to a call, it keeps a void CallIndex, i.e., the c_null_call_index.

Member Function Documentation

CallApiRc CallHdl::Accept (   ) 
 

Accepts an incoming (mobile terminated) voice call. Returns NoError if it has been successfully accepted. A CallSetupProgressMsg is sent during execution of Accept(). Refer to the documentation of CallApiRc for a detailed description of the return values.

Returns:
NoError - If executed successfully. In case of error one of the following values will be returned: CallDataLocked, ActiveCallDetected, InvalidCallIndex, VoidCallIndex or CallDisconnected.

void CallHdl::CancelRedialling (   )  [static]
 

With CancelRedialling the automatic redialling process can be stopped while a redialling timer is active and no call setup attempt is done. If a call setup attemt is ongoing, the redial process can be stopped using the Release method. CancelRedialling is always successful.

CallApiRc CallHdl::ExplicitCallTransfer (   ) 
 

The explicit call transfer supplementary service enables the served mobile subscriber to (A) who has two calls (remote parties B and C) to connect the other parties in the two calls and release the served mobile subscriber(A) own connection. Preconditions: If A-B is active A-C has to be in state waiting (C is MTC) and if call A-B is in held state, A-C has to be in state active or waiting. The method has to be applied to one of the respective calls. If the ECT has been successfully executed, the disconnect indications for the both calls will follow up synchronously.

Returns:
NoError - if excecuted successfully, InvalidCallIndex - if the CallHdl is invalid, VoidCallIndex - if no call exists for to the valid CallHdl, MptyCallDetected - if a MPTY call exists, SecondCallMissing - if only one call exists, SupplementaryServiceFailed - if ECT request is denied by the network. In this case the method GetLastErrorCause() of the CrssHandler returns the exact error code.

const PhoneNumber & CallHdl::GetPhoneNumber (   )  const
 

Returns a reference to a PhoneNumber object containing the phone number of a MOC or MTC. If the phone number has not yet been transmitted by network, the returned PhoneNumber is empty (MTC) If invoked during the setup phase of a MOC, the return value is the dialled phone number. The CallHdl shall contain a valid CallIndex, i.e., c_null_call_index < CallIndex < c_max_calls.

Returns:
A constant reference to a PhoneNumber.

CallApiRc CallHdl::Release (  TimeSpan *  calling_time = 0,
BOOLEAN  wait_condition = FALSE
)  [virtual]
 

Releases a mobile terminated or mobile originated voice call. May be invoked during call setup, call active and call held phase. The internal data will be immediately updated. There is no active wait for the networks release confirmation, since the confirmation will be generated by the protocol stack if the network fails to answer within 30 sec. The CallIndex of the CallHdl is set to c_null_call_index. Refer to the documentation of CallApiRc for a detailed description of the return values.

Parameters:
calling_time - Is set to the call duration (time span).
wait_condition TRUE for synchronous waiting of release
Returns:
NoError - If executed successfully. In case of error, one of the following values will be returned: CallDataLocked, InvalidCallIndex, VoidCallIndex.

Implements CallHdlBase.

CallApiRc CallHdl::Setup (  const PhoneNumber &  phone_no,
ClirMode  clir_mode = DontCare,
BOOLEAN  redial = FALSE,
const CugDescriptor *  cug = 0,
LineSelector  call_line = Line1,
BOOLEAN  ctm = FALSE,
CallEstCause  est_cause = HalfTchSpeech,
const EccCategory *  ecc_category = 0
) 
 

Establishes a mobile originated voice call. Assigns the CallIndex in the CallHdl as soon it is available by the protocol stack and returns NoError, if the call setup was successful. In case of any error, the CallIndex will be set to c_null_call_index. During the execution of Setup(const PhoneNumber & phone_no), several info-messages are sent (active wait loop). The messages supply information on setup progress and are the following: MocSetupAcceptMsg, ConnectionStatusMsg, and CallSetupProgressMsg. Refer to the documentation of CallApiRc for a detailed description of the return values. The CLIR mode is defaulted to the network settings. The CUG descriptor ist defaulted to the preferred CUG index and outgoing access enabled. Redialling is disabled by default.

Parameters:
phone_no The phone number of the call to be set up.
clir_mode SuppressPhoneNumber or DisplayPhoneNumber. By default DontCare will be used.
redial Enables automatic redialling if TRUE, disables automatic redialling otherwise. By default, the redialling feature is disabled.
cug A const pointer to the closed user group description. The default CUG information is defined as follows: The selected CUG is the PreferedCug, the CUG index is set to -1, and the outgoing access is not restricted, i.e., it is set to FALSE.
call_line Line1 or Line2. For using active line service ALS. By default Line1 will be used.
ctm Activate TTY(teletypewriter) also known as TDD(Telecommunication Device for Deaf).
est_cause Is HalfTchSpeech normaly. In case of emergency-call this must be set to EmergencyCall
ecc_category In case of a emergency-call the EccCategory can be set.
Returns:
NoError - If executed successfully. In case of error one of the following values will be returned: CallDataLocked, NoNetwork, ActiveCallDetected, SetupCallDetected, MaxCallCountExceeded, CallDisconnected, CallSetupRejected.
